ABUJA – The Federal Government has announced the resumption of domestic flights in the country. The Minister of Aviation, Hadi Sirika, announced this in a tweet on Wednesday. According to him, the Abuja and Lagos airports will resume domestic operations on July 8, while the Kano, Port Harcourt, Owerri and Maiduguri airports would resume on the 11th. Other airports are also expected to resume operations on the 15th. Sirika, however, noted that a date for the international airports will be announced in due course. (Channels TV) The Federal Government has confirmed that a simulation trial of domestic flights will be carried out at the Murtala Muhammed Airport in Lagos this Saturday, according to a report by Daily Post. It said the aim of the simulation is in preparation to reopen the country’s airspace to commercial flights.… June 23, 2020 In "Politics" •Minister of Aviation, Hadi Sirika LAGOS - The Federal Government on Saturday said that the Nigerian Civil Aviation Authority (NCAA) is 90 percent ready to open up the airways for domestic flights in the country to fly. It said even though it is not 100 percent satisfied with what it’s… June 27, 2020 In "News" •Hadi Sirika, aviation minister ABUJA - The Nigerian Civil Aviation Authority (NCAA) has begun an investigation into the reason why an aircraft belonging to a British company was operating commercial flights into the Murtala Muhammed International Airport, Lagos. The aircraft, a legacy 600 with registration G-PRFX, was impounded by the… May 18, 2020 In "News"